\section{State Validity Checking}

OMPL requires a state validity checker to determine whether a given
robot configuration is collision-free. In this tutorial, we used
a custom validity checker that uses PyRoKi to detect both self-collisions
and collisions with the environment.

\subsection{Code explanation}

\begin{lstlisting}
self.robot_coll = robot_coll
self.plane_coll = plane_coll
self.robot: pk.Robot = robot
self.obstacles = {}
\end{lstlisting}
We initialize the collision checker with the robot collision model, ground plane, and robot kinematics.

\begin{lstlisting}
def set_obs(self, obstacle_dict: dict):
    self.obstacles = obstacle_dict or {}
\end{lstlisting}
We update the set of obstacles in the environment.

\begin{lstlisting}
def global_obs_list(self):
    world = [self.plane_coll]
\end{lstlisting}
We add all the obstacles to check whether it collides with the robot.
In this line, we first add ground plane into our obstacle set.

\begin{lstlisting}
for _, obs in self.obstacles.items():
    world.append(
        Sphere.from_center_and_radius(
            np.asarray(obs["position"], dtype=np.float32),
            float(obs["radius"]),
        )
    )
return world
\end{lstlisting}
In this for loop, we traverse through obstacle dictionary and change
each obstacle as a collision-checkable sphere object.\\
TLDR, this function constructs a list of world collision geometry.

\begin{lstlisting}
def is_state_valid(self, q: np.ndarray):
    q = np.asarray(q, dtype=np.float32)
    world_list = self.global_obs_list()
\end{lstlisting}
In this function, we first convert the joint configuration into float32
and create a world collision object.

\begin{lstlisting}
for world_coll in world_list:
    world_dist = self.robot_coll.compute_world_collision_distance(
        self.robot, q, world_coll
    )
    if float(jnp.min(world_dist)) <= -1e-2:
        print("world collision")
        return False
\end{lstlisting}
In this for loop, we computes the distance between each object with each collision sphere of robot.
if the distance is $<$ 0, it means the obstacle collides with the robot.

\begin{lstlisting}
self_dist = self.robot_coll.compute_self_collision_distance(self.robot, q)
if float(jnp.min(self_dist)) <= -5e-2:
    print("self collision")
    return False
\end{lstlisting}
Here, we calculates the distance between the robot links.
this function checks for self-collision by computing the distance between the robot links.
the is\_state\_valid(self,q) returns True if the configuration is collision-free

