\section{Running the RRTConnect Planner}

Once the start and goal configurations are defined, the RRTConnect
planner from OMPL is used to compute a collision-free joint-space
trajectory between them.

\subsection{Code Explanation}

\begin{lstlisting}
def __init__(self, collision_checker, lower_limits, upper_limits, dim):
    self.collision_checker = collision_checker
    self.dim = dim
    self.lower_limits = np.array(lower_limits, dtype=float)
    self.upper_limits = np.array(upper_limits, dtype=float)
\end{lstlisting}
we first initialize the necessary fields.\\
dim : dimenstion of the state space\\
lower/upper limits: joint limit of each links.

\begin{lstlisting}
def plan(self, start_config: np.ndarray, goal_config: np.ndarray,
            timeout: float, obstacles: dict = None)
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{lstlisting}
start_config = np.asarray(start_config, dtype=float).reshape(-1)
goal_config  = np.asarray(goal_config, dtype=float).reshape(-1)
\end{lstlisting}
For the plan function we first convert the start/goal into 1D vector.

\begin{lstlisting}
self.collision_checker.set_obs(obstacles)
\end{lstlisting}
Before planning, we update current obstable location to CollisionChecker class.

\begin{lstlisting}
for i in range(self.dim):
    bounds.setLow(i, float(self.lower_limits[i]))
    bounds.setHigh(i, float(self.upper_limits[i]))
space.setBounds(bounds)
\end{lstlisting}
We incorporate the joint limits into the state space bounds so that OMPL samples only valid states within the allowable joint ranges.

\begin{lstlisting}
og.SimpleSetup(space)
\end{lstlisting}
This line create a high-level planning interface that bundles the state space, validity checking,
planner configuration, and solution handling into a single object.

\begin{lstlisting}
def _is_valid(state):
    q = np.array([state[i] for i in range(self.dim)], dtype=float)
    return bool(self.collision_checker.is_state_valid(q))
\end{lstlisting}
While planning we call this function to check whether the trajectory is collision-free for each sample.

\begin{lstlisting}
start = space.allocState()
goal  = space.allocState()
for i in range(self.dim):
    start[i] = float(start_config[i])
    goal[i]  = float(goal_config[i])
\end{lstlisting}
We create a State object and allocate an adequate values.

\begin{lstlisting}
si = ss.getSpaceInformation()
ss.setPlanner(og.RRTConnect(si))
solved = ss.solve(timeout)
\end{lstlisting}
First, we retrieve the SpaceInformation object, which encapsulates the state space, joint bounds, and collision checking.
We then configure the planner by instantiating RRT-Connect with this space information.
Finally, we call solve() to execute the motion planning process within a specified time limit.

\begin{lstlisting}
if solved:
    ss.simplifySolution()
\end{lstlisting}
We post-processes the computed path to make it shorter and smoother by removing unnecessary detours.

